<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / International Company News: Apple plans cost shake-up in
wake of heavy loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
APPLE Computer reported heavy losses for its third quarter, after higher
than expected charges to cover the cost of 2,500 job cuts announced earlier
this month. The personal computer company said it intends to 'dramatically
reduce its cost structure' to boost profitability.
Apple took a pre-tax charge of Dollars 320.9m for the job cuts and other
cost reduction measures. After charges, the company reported a net loss for
the quarter of Dollars 188.3m, or Dollars 1.63 per share. For the same
period last year, Apple had net profits of Dollars 131.7m, or Dollars 1.07
per share.
Net revenues for the quarter were Dollars 1.86bn, up 7 per cent from Dollars
1.74bn in last year's third quarter.
The ongoing price wars in the PC industry, as well as weaker than expected
sales in Europe, contributed to the disappointing third-quarter results,
Apple said.
It said itmore aggressively on price in its personal computer business,
while reducing its cost structure to compensate for lower gross profit
margins.
'We're confident we can put our business back on a growth path by
aggressively pursuing market share while offering innovative technology. At
the same time, we must significantly, and permanently, lower our cost of
doing business,' said Michael Spindler, Apple president and chief executive
officer.
Mr Spindler was appointed chief executive, succeeding Mr John Sculley, who
remains chairman, last month.
Apple has cut prices on many of its Macintosh products over the past three
months, including price reductions on its popular PowerBook portable
computers last week.
'Early indications suggest that our most recent price reductions are
accelerating our unit shipments,' Mr Spindler said. 'Development of new
Macintosh desktop systems and new PowerBook notebook computers are on
track.'
Apple's new businesses' personal digital assistants, servers, and software
products, promise to contribute to revenue and profits in the coming fiscal
year, he added. 'As a result, we see excellent opportunities for growth in
Apple's future.'
For the nine-month period, Apple reported net sales of Dollars 5.8bn, up
from Dollars 5.3bn in the same period last year.
Net profits were Dollars 83.9m, or 70 cents per share, down from Dollars
432.8m, or Dollars 3.52 per share a year earlier.
</TEXT>
