<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / UK Company News: Revised rules on large trade disclosure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE TRADES on the London Stock Exchange will not have to be reported for
up to a week after they are executed under new rules agreed yesterday by the
Exchange's board, writes Norma Cohen.
The rules, described as an 'interim measure', are nominally aimed at
improving the liquidity in so-called second and third-tier stocks - those
whose market capital ranks them in the bottom two thirds of all shares
traded.
The rules are also expected to boost the profits of the Exchange's
marketmaking members who place their own capital at risk when they agree to
buy large blocks of shares from clients without knowing whether they will be
able to resell them quickly or profitably.
The rules, set to take effect by the end of this year, will be in force for
six to 12 months while regulators assess their effects. If there is no
increase in liquidity among smaller stocks, regulators may ask the Exchange
to scrap the rule.
Under the rule, details of trades 75 times the 'normal market size' for
transactions in any particular stock do not have to be published on the
Exchange's SEAQ price reporting screen for up to five days after completion
or until the marketmaker has unwound or hedged 90 per cent of the risk. All
trades will have to be reported to the Exchange, however.
For large stocks where underlying options are traded, this could include
hedging with exchange-traded derivative instruments. Alternatively, it could
involve the sale of the shares to a third party.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-13933</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DGPB4AEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930716
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / UK Company News: Buoyant markets help lift Jones Stroud to
Pounds 6.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JONES STROUD (Holdings), the textiles and electrical accessories group,
yesterday reported pre-tax profits ahead from Pounds 4.83m to Pounds 6.51m
for the year to March 31.
The increase was flattered by a Pounds 609,000 exceptional provision taken
in the previous period. Turnover improved to Pounds 70.9m (Pounds 65.4m).
Mr Philip Jones, chairman, said: 'The rise in profits is due to increased
turnover and more buoyancy in our markets, both in the UK and overseas.'
'We have some new products,' he added, 'and we found late last year that the
recession lifted a bit. We were the first into the recession and presumably
we will be the first out of it as well.'
The group supplies the hosiery, electrical engineering, consumer durables,
clothing and aluminium tube markets. The textiles market was now the
strongest.
Mr Jones said two plants had recently been closed and the vulcanised fibre
business consolidated onto one site. The group had incurred some trading
loss in the previous period because of this.
An increased final dividend of 5.5p gives a total for the year of 8.8p (8p);
earnings per share were 24.85p (18.05p).
</TEXT>
