<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Government plans wider access to information:
Whistle-blowers may be protected by 'harm tests'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOVES TO sweep away of some of the secrecy of government came a step closer
yesterday when Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister,
announced plans to increase public access to information.
The plans include a code of practice, new statutory rights and the
introduction of 'harm tests' to prevent whistle-blowers being penalised for
revealing information that does no harm.
Unveiling a white paper which outlines proposals designed to bring greater
openness into Whitehall and other parts of the public sector, Mr Waldegrave
said that public access to information would be restricted only where there
were good reasons.
Despite continuing pressure from opposition MPs and campaigners, he was
unapologetic that the government had decided against a full freedom of
information act. He insisted his proposals were practical steps which met
the main aims of freedom of information legislation. They also maintained
parliamentary accountability rather than handing the issue over to the
courts.
'These proposals lay down a sure and lasting foundation for more open public
administration and government,' he said.
The proposals include a code of practice which would require Whitehall
departments to comply with reasonable requests for information. This could
extend to other organisations such as the National Health Service and local
authorities. The code would be policed by the parliamentary ombudsman.
There will be statutory rights to personal information and to health and
safety information.
There is unlikely to be time for government legislation in the coming
session of parliament, but a backbench MP could sponsor the measures in the
limited time available for this type of bill.
Maintaining the momentum behind the plans will be a critical test of Mr
Waldegrave's ability to sustain pressure on Whitehall. Some departments,
said to include the Treasury and the department of health, have resisted
aspects of the plans.
Tory MPs said the plans had gone beyond their expectations, but opposition
MPs and campaigners for greater freedom of information were more guarded in
their welcome.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, the shadow public services minister, condemned the white
paper as fundamentally flawed because it left ministers to decide what
information should be made available. 'There are a lot of nice words, a lot
of good intentions, a lot of rhetoric but in the end there is a deep failure
to deliver open government,' she said.
White paper would widen information access, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
