<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Matrix case would see little change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUGH the furore that surrounded the Matrix Churchill trial might have been
one of the factors prodding the government into reforming its freedom of
information policy, yesterday's white paper seems unlikely to have made much
difference to the issues that dominated the case.
For although the paper promises better rights for individuals wishing to
gain access to their personal files, it does not guarantee that a government
department would reveal the type of documents that proved so central to the
Matrix Churchill case.
The controversy about the release of documents in the case centred on two
issues.
The first was why the government had been able, in the late 1980s, to
withhold from parliament documents showing that it had privately changed its
policy towards arms sales to Iraq - a change that led companies like
Matrix-Churchill to believe they could deal with Iraq.
Under the new code of practice, the Ministry of Defence would, in theory,
now be under considerably greater pressure to reveal this type of policy
change. In addition to parliamentary questioning, the department could also
face policing from the parliamentary ombudsman if it failed to open its
files, and would have to comply with written requests for information.
But, since the code reiterates that parliament remains the main vehicle for
prompting disclosure, critics yesterday pointed out that without
parliamentary pressure, there would still be no means of forcing disclosure.
Mr Maurice Frankel, from the Campaign for Freedom of Information, yesterday
said: 'Under a Freedom of Information act that would have been a disclosable
document - it was only a minor policy change. That is not the case in this
white paper.'
The second issue was whether government ministers should be able to use
public interest immunity certificates to prevent the release of sensitive
documents.
On that matter, the white paper promises little change. Although, in the
Matrix case, the application was overturned, the white paper envisages that
ministers will still be able to use the immunity clause in cases affecting
national security.
Mr Paul Henderson, a former Matrix director, said yesterday: 'It was only
the release of documents that stopped us from being convicted.'
</TEXT>
