<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Straw warns on Banham review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday issued a warning to the government not to tamper with the
Banham review of local government structure, Alison Smith writes.
Both ministers and officials within the Department of the Environment are
known to be unhappy with the review so far and to be considering ways in
which its future activities could be curtailed.
One suggestion is that after the first areas have been reviewed, future
tranches of work would be optional, and the structure of councils in some
areas would not be reviewed unless there was a substantial move for change.
But Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, called instead yesterday
for an expanded commission, a faster process of review and new guidelines
covering matters such as identifying natural communities and costing
proposals.
In a letter to Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, Mr Straw said
Labour was still committed to unitary authorities based on district
councils, in place of the current two-tier structure.
