<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unions cool on Smith deal for
Labour reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING trade unions yester-day gave a frosty reception to the deal Mr John
Smith has proposed for reforming Labour's union links, highlighting the
difficulties he still faces in avoiding a row at September's party
conference.
Although Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU transport union, and
Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, were careful not to
deliberately re-fuel their confrontation with the Labour leader, it was
clear that they were unhappy with a deal Mr Smith reached on Wednesday.
Mr Edmonds is under pressure particularly from 'moderniser' Labour MPs to
compromise, because of the damaging impact of the confrontation on Labour's
image. He faced angry protests at a meeting of Labour MPs on Wednesday
night. One said the level of personal bitterness had been 'extraordinary'.
Mr Smith has expressed delight at proposals drawn up by Labour's internal
union links committee on reforming leadership elections, the selection of
parliamentary candidates, and on the 'block vote' at Labour conferences.
Yesterday Mr Smith predicted a 'gathering of support' around the plans which
will be discussed by Labour's ruling National Executive Committee on Monday.
Labour officials and MPs were hopeful that enough union votes would swing
behind the Labour leader to avoid a potentially damaging conference defeat.
Among Mr Smith's main union opponents, there was a recognition that he had
compromised a little, particularly on the election of future party leaders
where 'individual' union members would continue to have a vote in a reformed
electoral college.
But there was bitterness at what was seen as an attempt by Mr Smith to
bounce unions into accepting a deal.
Mr Morris said reports of an agreement with the unions were 'not true' and
that for union links with Labour to be 'properly maintained' there had to be
'a genuine opportunity for the voice of trade unions to be collectively
expressed in all important decisions, including the selection of
parliamentary candidates'.
He added: 'It is our view that the proposals emanating from the working
group fall well short of this principle.'
The GMB is not opposed to all parts of Mr Smith's reforms, but it objects
particularly to his proposal that unions should pay a membership fee, in
addition to the political levy, in order to become 'registered' union
members entitled to vote when constituency parties select candidates.
There is scope for compromise over the summer, however, because the GMB
backs the idea of a register of Labour-supporting union members. A deal
could be struck on Mr Smith's definition of a 'register' and on the extra
fee that union members would have to pay.
</TEXT>
