<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Eternal problems of Church funding: The crisis forcing the
General Synod to reform Anglican finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW PEOPLE attend their local church because they want to make it more
financially efficient.
Churches, like charities and voluntary organisations in general, draw
support from those who are more likely to spend money on worthwhile causes
than worry about cash flow and balanced budgets.
Such values pose particular difficulties for the Church of England. Its
status as established church, custodian of historic monuments and
stage-manager of lavish state occasions can lead to it being viewed, even by
its active members, like a public library or the National Health Service -
something everyone takes for granted but feels no personal responsibility
for having to finance.
These ingrained attitudes collided with plain talking at the summer session
of the Church's General Synod which ended in York on Tuesday. The Church of
England is in financial trouble which, synod members were warned, is going
to demand radical changes in the way it operates. By the end of the century
it must be transformed from a largely centralised institution, heavily
dependent on investment income from the Church Commissioners - who are
responsible for the Church's main investments - to one where individual
parishes pay their own way.
For the Church Commissioners' assets are not what they once were. About half
are in property, and the recent decline in the market was the main factor in
the Church's income-producing assets losing more than Pounds 800m in value
between 1989 and last year.
The Lambeth Group, a committee set up last year following criticism of the
commissioners' management of the Church's assets, is due to report soon. If
it shares the view of Sir Michael Colman, chairman of Reckitt &amp; Colman and
the first church estates commissioner, it will conclude that storing up so
much treasure in property holdings in the 1980s left the commissioners
seriously exposed.
However critical the report proves to be, the reality is that the Church has
regarded the commissioners as a perpetual taxpayer, on whose back
improvements in clergy stipends, pensions and other well-intentioned
developments have been built.
The Rt Rev John Wayne, Bishop of Chelmsford and chairman of the Lambeth
Group, says reliance on the commissioners' income has led to the assumption
that 'an Anglican pound was always worth Pounds 3 or Pounds 4' compared with
other denominations that have to raise more funds locally.
Other churches have therefore been more successful at fund-raising. A
typical Church of England worshipper gives between Pounds 2.50 and Pounds
3.00 a week - respectable by general charity fund-raising standards, but
little more than half the 5 per cent of net income that the Church
encourages.
In the Chelmsford diocese itself, which covers Essex and parts of east
London, one-third of the parishes subsidise the other two-thirds. A study is
being undertaken to discover the characteristics of a financially successful
parish but what is already clear is that the underperforming two-thirds
include parishes in the more affluent parts of Essex.
A deteriorating financial position will bring an increased emphasis on
fund-raising to the Church of England, both by trying to persuade existing
worshippers to give higher amounts, and encouraging more people to go to
church.
The Church has already made its first moves into corporate videos and
television advertising, and fund-raising styles may become more modern.
Mr Alan McLintock, chairman of the central board of finance, spoke
approvingly at the synod of high quality events with personalised
invitations and good food, compared with the more common existing method -
an evening of discussion in the church hall 'to the accompaniment of fairly
typical church refreshments which I can describe bleakly as sausage rolls
and coffee'.
Even if the Church surmounts the considerable hurdles of increasing its
local-level income substantially, other problems will arise.
One of the most fundamental of these concerns the radical change in
relationship that would be likely to develop between financially independent
parishes paying the stipends of their own clergy and the Church's national
leadership.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8661 Religious Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
