<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 93 / Council spending to increase 3.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL government spending will be allowed to rise by 3.5 per cent next year,
according to a ministerial letter leaked to the Local Government Chronicle.
The letter was sent in May by Mr Michael Howard - then environment secretary
 -to Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury.
In the letter Mr Howard says that councils need an extra Pounds 2.14bn 'to
protect local authority services', according to the Department of the
Environment's calculations. However, he says he is prepared 'to live with'
Pounds 1.44bn. Local authority associations have requested an extra Pounds
5.14bn.
The 3.5 per cent rise would affect councils' standard spending assessments,
which determine how much grant they receive from central government, and
cover all council-controlled services. Standard spending assessments are
also used to determine the level at which council budgets may be 'capped' by
government.
Mr Howard suggests that the savings could be achieved either through pay
restraint, or through forcing councils to find greater efficiency savings.
However, he says: 'It requires an act of faith to suppose that authorities
will look for savings rather than making cuts; their recent track record is
not impressive.'
The letter also recommends a 'rapid phasing out' of transitional relief for
the council tax by the end of next year. He says: 'A sudden increase in
council tax levels in the second year could all too easily swing the public
against the tax.'
Local authorities are to meet Mr John Gummer, Mr Howard's successor as
environment secretary, next Thursday to discuss spending plans.
</TEXT>
