<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Unilever dives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anglo-Dutch foods group Unilever recorded its biggest turnover for nearly
four years and a second day's steep decline as fears resurfaced over the
value of brands ahead of today's press conference on pricing strategy by
Procter &amp; Gamble.
Selected food manufacturing and drinks stocks weakened as investors took
fright at the prospect of price wars, particularly in markets where margins
are already under pressure. In Unilever's case this would apply to the
detergents business, where P&amp;G has indicated that it intends to bring
pressure to bear.
Unilever shares followed Monday's fall of 25 with a further drop of 24
yesterday to 953p. Turnover was a hefty 7.4m, its biggest since November
1989. Among other strong 'brand' groups, Cadbury-Schweppes weakened 9 to
439p, Tate &amp; Lyle 5 to 385p, Grand Metropolitan 6 to 409p and Guinness 13 to
454p.
