<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 93 / International Company News: Charles Schwab ahead at Dollars
31.6m but growth slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHARLES Schwab, the largest discount brokerage house in the US, yesterday
reported a big increase in second-quarter profits to Dollars 31.6m, up from
the Dollars 18.5m earned in the same quarter of 1992.
Like other securities houses, however, Schwab's profits in the second
quarter were slightly lower than in the first period of the year, when the
firm earned a record Dollars 35.4m.
The downturn in earnings suggests that while Wall Street continues to
benefit from a two-year boom in stock market and underwriting activity, the
pace of growth has slackened over the past three months.
Yesterday, the San-Francisco based firm said that client trading activity in
June was the softest of any month this year.
Mr Charles Schwab, chairman, said he also expected retail trading activity
to weaken in the third quarter, although he believed the firm's results for
that period would still be an improvement on the same period of 1992, when
Schwab earned a below-average Dollars 7.8m.
Commission revenues rose 34 per cent to Dollars 136m, mutual fund service
fees by 53 per cent to Dollars 23.1m, and principal transactions revenues by
30 per cent to Dollars 39.3m.
Non-interest expenses rose 26 per cent to Dollars 180.4m, primarily due to
increased trading activity and an 8.5 per cent rise in client assets to a
record Dollars 79.2bn.
Shares in Schwab rose initially on the earnings announcement, but then fell
back from close to a year-high on profit-taking. By the end of trading the
stock was at Dollars 27 5/8, down Dollars 1 3/8.
