<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: UK inflation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If Tuesday's industrial production and yesterday's inflation figures had not
arrived on government notepaper, the casual observer might have thought they
related to Japan. The UK does seem to have survived the first wave of price
pressure from devaluation, due to low wage inflation and a yawning gap in
the productive potential of the UK economy. Manufacturers are even managing
to restore margins despite subdued price rises. One area where this may not
be true is food retailing, where costs are rising but retail prices are
under pressure. Those fat margins built up in recession may soon start to
slim.
</TEXT>
