<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lee Kuan Yew, former leader of Singapore, talks to David Lomax in Business
Matters which also reports on the island's business prospects. In 30 years
it has developed from a ramshackle dockyard into one of the most influential
business centres in the world, but the programme asks whether Lee Kuan Yew's
autocratic habits will be appropriate for a new generation (7.40 BBC2).
Crime Limited would be a healthier programme if the makers would stop
pretending that it was performing some sort of high minded social service
and admitted that it is doing just what all the other ambulance-chasing
series are doing: chasing the ratings. It would be more honest to promote it
in the style of the old evening paper fudge boards: 'Horrible murder: full
details' (8.30 BBC1).
Given that the US did not make war on Iraq because of threats to American
oil supplies (the suggestion was vehemently rejected) but because a
sovereign state had been invaded, how should we explain America's failure
for 40 years to fight a war on behalf of Tibet? Under The Sun reports on the
Chinese occupation (9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
