<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 93 / MPs condemn lack of research for legal aid reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM KING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government acted in ignorance when it reformed the legal aid system, a
committee of backbench MPs said yesterday.
The Commons public accounts committee expressed concern that the Lord
Chancellor's department did not have enough information about the likely
impact of changes to legal aid introduced on April 1.
In a report published yesterday the committee acknowledges that the Lord
Chancellor's intention in changing eligibility for legal aid was to contain
the rise in spending while targeting aid at those who needed it most.
But the report says that the department's officials 'did not know the number
of adults who would no longer be eligible for support, and were unable to
confirm or reject the worrying estimates that had been made by the legal
profession'. It adds: 'The department had no figures on the likely impact of
their measures on the number of people who represented themselves and on the
extra costs and delays that might be incurred.'
According to the report, neither the department nor the Legal Aid Board had
any information or analysis on why offers of legal aid were not taken up,
even though that could help in forecasting and monitoring legal aid
spending.
In 1991-92, 2.8m people were assisted by legal aid at a cost of Pounds
947.1m, an increase of nearly 40 per cent on the previous year. Spending is
expected to rise to Pounds 1.1bn in 1992-93 and to Pounds 1.5bn in 1995-96.
The MPs argued that whatever the eligibility framework, the biggest
opportunity for saving on legal aid spending was controlling the cost of
cases.
Court cases are now much more costly in real terms than 10 years ago, the
report says. The MPs urge more control over the assessment and payment of
the costs of court cases and action 'to eliminate additional costs arising
from delays and shortcomings within the systems of civil and criminal
justice'.
In his annual report on the court service, also published yesterday, Lord
Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, says that his department's priority will be to
control legal aid costs and spending on the courts while maintaining
standards of service.
The Administration of Legal Aid in England and Wales (HC 459). HMSO. Pounds
13.25.
Lord Chancellor's Department Court Service Annual Report, HMSO. Pounds
13.00.
</TEXT>
